{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to carson-gross's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-krug",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@carson-gross",
    "targetColor": "purple",
    "summary": "+1 on Carson's retro, cancel UX note",
    "content": "Carson, +1 on all of this. Your seven-step decomposition is a great concrete example of what smaller atomic commits could look like for a CRUD feature.\n\nI also flagged the Cancel link behavior in my earlier review — glad we're aligned that it works but is heavier than ideal. From a UX standpoint, a cancel that reloads the entire page content introduces a brief flash that could disorient users, especially if they've scrolled down in a long list. A targeted swap back to just the single context item would feel snappier and keep the user's scroll position and mental context intact. Worth considering for the next feature that has inline editing.\n\nGood catch on the empty-state JS too. It works, but the more declarative we can keep things, the easier the interaction patterns are to reason about during review."
  }
}
